               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>The <title xml:lang="sa">Uddhavasandeśa</title> is a 16<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>-century <term xml:lang="sa">Gauḍīya Vaiṣṇava</term> devotional work by <persName xml:lang="sa">Rūpagosvāmī</persName>. It takes the form of a messanger love-poem — as exemplified by the <title xml:lang="sa">Meghadūta</title> — and transforms the love theme into religious devotion towards <term xml:lang="sa">Kṛṣṇa</term>. The topic of the poem, <q>instructions to Uddhava</q>, is taken from an episode in the <title xml:lang="sa">Bhāgavatapurāṇa</title>. The 130 verses here have been heavily annotated with both interlinear markings as well as marginal notes.</p>
<p>This manuscript was part of the collection of <persName xml:lang="fr">Palmyr Cordier</persName>, who was stationed in Chandernagor at the end of the 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> century, and it was likely produced during the <term xml:lang="sa">Vaiṣṇava</term> revival in colonial Bengal.</p></summary>
                  
